      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here are the results for **\"The Minimum Description Length Principle\"** by Peter D. Grünwald (MIT Press, 2007):\n\n## Book Details\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "*The Minimum Description Length Principle* by Peter D. Grünwald was published on March 23, 2007 by The MIT Press. It is 736 pages with 12 illustrations."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n- **Hardcover ISBN:** "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "978-0-262-07281-6"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n- **Paperback ISBN:** "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "9780262529631"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n- **Series:** "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Adaptive Computation and Machine Learning"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n- **Foreword by:** "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Jorma Rissanen"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n## About the Author\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Peter D. Grünwald is a researcher at CWI, the National Research Institute for Mathematics and Computer Science, Amsterdam, the Netherlands."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "He is also affiliated with EURANDOM, the European Research Institute for the Study of Stochastic Phenomena, Eindhoven, the Netherlands."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n## Book Description\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The minimum description length (MDL) principle is a powerful method of inductive inference, the basis of statistical modeling, pattern recognition, and machine learning."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "It holds that the best explanation, given a limited set of observed data, is the one that permits the greatest compression of the data."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "MDL methods are particularly well-suited for dealing with model selection, prediction, and estimation problems in situations where the models under consideration can be arbitrarily complex, and overfitting the data is a serious concern."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n## Structure\n\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Part I provides a basic introduction to MDL and an overview of the concepts in statistics and information theory needed to understand MDL."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Part II treats universal coding, the information-theoretic notion on which MDL is built, and Part III gives a formal treatment of MDL theory as a theory of inductive inference based on universal coding."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Part IV provides a comprehensive overview of the statistical theory of exponential families with an emphasis on their information-theoretic properties."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\nThe book is available from MIT Press, Amazon, and other retailers. A PDF version is also hosted at [CWI's institutional repository](https://ir.cwi.nl/pub/11997/11997D.pdf)."
      }
    ],
